<TEXT>
a washington teenager was arrested tuesday on 
charges of selling the crack cocaine that president bush displayed 
on television to illustrate the seriousness of the nations drug 
problems 
keith jackson 18 was indicted earlier in the day by a federal 
grand jury on four counts of unlawfully distributing crack and one 
count of using a telephone to help arrange an alleged sale 
the alleged distribution started in april on one occasion near 
eastern high school in washington in july according to the 
indictment 
jackson was picked up at his home in southeast washington by 
city police and drug enforcement administration agents said dea 
spokesman cornelius dougherty 
us magistrate pattrick attridge ordered jackson held without 
bond pending another hearing wednesday 
in a sept 5 televised speech bush held up a clear plastic bag 
containing a handful of crack nuggets and said they had been seized 
across the street from the white house a few days previously 
the alleged dealer was lured to lafayette park not one of 
washingtons drug markets four days before by undercover drug 
agents after white house staffers asked for a sample from the 
vicinity of the white house to show that dealing could happen 
anywhere 
officials of the dea said they had planned to make the purchase 
a few blocks away before the white house request 
the transaction with an undercover dea agent was photographed 
but the dealer was not taken into custody then because agents hoped 
he would sell a larger amount later and identify his supply 
organization officials said 
a planned arrest last week fell through when the suspect did not 
show up 
