range from communist to conservative their bitter closeddoor 
nomination meeting contrasted sharply with the lively sandinista 
convention 
ortega promised fair elections in return for a central american 
agreement to disband the ussupported contras by early december 
while that date might not be met it appears that the end of the 
war is in sight 
the war against the sandinista government is paralyzed because 
of the peace accords said wycliff diego leader of a major 
indian resistance group from eastern nicaragua 
diego became the latest leader to drop out of the armed 
resistance when he said monday that he would return to nicaragua 
this week to investigate setting up a political party and 
supporting mrs chamorro 
but while the electoral process seems to be drawing in the 
opposition and weakening the armed resistance the sandinista 
platform slogan everything will be better exposed a crack in 
an otherwise slick surface 
the slogan is a reminder if any were needed that nicaraguas 
economy has gone steadily downhill to the point that it rivals 
haiti as the poorest nation in the americas 
in an effort to control hyperinflation the government has had 
to implement an austerity program that left thousands jobless 
the sandinistas blame their problems on the war and a us 
economic boycott but promises of better times ahead are being met 
with skepticism by voters who must struggle daily to make ends meet 
with less money higher prices and food shortages 
it was no surprise that ortega and vice president sergio ramirez 
were renominated they have worked together smoothly in the past 
ortega is the tough firebrand exguerrilla who doesnt miss a 
chance to bait the us government while ramirez is the cool 
moderatetoned polished intellectual 
in his acceptance speech ortega predicted the sandinista would 
win and that the united states will have to accept an 
understanding with nicaragua 
the bush administration has already given signs of 
accommodation recently a top state department official visited 
nicaragua and met with ortega the first time that has happened in 
years 
ortega knows that winning us acceptance however reluctant is 
probably vital to economic recovery but also that this depends on 
his party winning the elections cleanly 
the sandinistas are intent on having the vote declared free and 
fair and have invited international observers including former 
president jimmy carter who monitored panamas presidential 
election in may and called it a fraud 
in an editorial mrs chamorros newspaper la prensa said 
ortegas speech showed the sandinistas were depending on sterile 
antiamericanism and did not have a vision of the future to sell 
the electorate 
the bush administration is trying to devise a way to assist 
nicaraguas fledgling democratic process without providing direct 
support to the opposition 
a figure of 9 million has been mentioned by us congressional 
sources that would be more than 4 for each of nicaraguas 19 
million voters but there are no signs of any big money yet 
the sandinistas has already called on its organizations which 
cover every neighborhood in the country to begin housetohouse 
campaigning using the threat of a superfinanced opposition for 
motivation 
the wellplanned sandinista convention to which the press and 
the diplomatic corps were invited contrasted sharply with tense 
deliberations of the political parties comprising the national 
opposition union 
the uno as it is known for its spanish initials chose virgilio 
godoy as mrs chamorros running mate three weeks ago but the 
choice almost split the coalition 
the choice was considered important because many view mrs 
chamorro as a figurehead conservatives supported businessman 
enrique bolanos but godoys supporters said bolanos would tilt the 
ticket too far to the right 
