<TEXT>
gov rudy perpich said tuesday he is 
asking the us supreme court to review an appellate decision 
upholding a law that stripped governors of their veto power over 
national guard training missions 
congress enacted the law known as the montgomery amendment 
after several governors in 1985 and 1986 objected to deployment of 
national guard personnel on maneuvers in central america where the 
governors felt there was a danger of involvement in wars 
the law presents a states rights issue of historical 
importance perpich said at a news conference because of 
conflicting decisions in the lower courts this issue warrants a 
final resolution by the supreme court 
perpich said he has never disapproved of any federal training 
deployment of the minnesota national guard but is challenging the 
laws constitutionality because it invades on a governors 
authority 
perpich initially challenged the montgomery amendment on jan 
28 1987 the amendment to a 1986 defense bill says governors may 
not withhold their consent to national guard missions because of 
any objection to the location purpose type or schedule of such 
active duty 
the amendment was upheld in us district court but a 
threejudge panel of the 8th us circuit court of appeals ruled it 
was unconstitutional at the request of the us department of 
justice the full 8th circuit considered the matter and on june 
28 it held 72 that the law is constitutional 
minnesotas lawsuit contends the law violates the militia clause 
of the constitution which reserves to states authority to direct 
or consent to peacetime training of the national guard 
a statement issued tuesday by the office of the amendments 
author rep gv montgomery dmiss said the case already has 
been argued exhaustively 
the courts have ruled the amendment to be constitutional 
montgomery said its time now to let the national guard get back 
to the business of training and away from the courtroom it would 
be a terrible mistake to deny our guard personnel the chance to 
train in real world conditions that cant be duplicated at bases in 
the united states 
jack tunheim minnesotas chief deputy attorney general said a 
decision from the supreme court on whether it will hear the case is 
expected in two to three months 
the supreme courts refusal to hear a similar challenge to the 
law filed by massachusetts and rejected by the 1st us circuit 
court of appeals should have no bearing on whether the high court 
considers minnesotas challenge tunheim said 
that case was not nearly as welldeveloped as the minnesota 
case tunheim said the 1st circuit issued a onesentence order 
affirming the law while the decisions in the minnesota case have 
prompted lengthy dissents tunheim said 
