<TEXT>
urging closer scrutiny of third world defense 
budgets world bank president barber conable said tuesday poor 
countries spent more on the military than on health and education 
combined at times during the past decade 
but let us hope that in the changing political climate of the 
1990s resources are increasingly allocated to more productive 
purposes he said in an address prepared for the banks annual 
meeting 
as a whole low income countries currently spend around 20 
percent of their funds on defense conable said despite cuts in 
other necessities the 200 billion which the developing world 
spends annually on the military has largely been protected he 
said 
the united states spent about 290 billion on the military in 
fiscal year 1989 or about 29 percent of the national budget 
conable said its time for developing countries on one side 
and their arms suppliers on the other to adapt to a world 
where budgets are tight 
it is important to place military spending on the same footing 
as other fiscal decisions to examine possible tradeoffs more 
systematically and to explore ways to bring military spending into 
better balance with development priorities he said 
every country has the right and duty to defend itself and in 
evaluating military expenditures governments should be realistic 
but they also should remember the human consequences of these 
choices said conable who as a former us congressman had some 
experience with gunsvsbutter tradeoffs 
military spending is a sensitive component of the fiscal 
problem that can no longer be neglected conable said because 
arms are often a prime source of external debt accounting for a 
third or more of the interest due by some major third world 
debtridden countries 
