<TEXT>
the soviet union while accepting a us 
call to slash chemical weapons stockpiles insisted tuesday on a 
different approach keyed to halting production of the deadly arms 
a cessation of further output of poison gas must be part of 
the parcel senior soviet negotiator viktor p karpov said 
even so the white house welcomed soviet acceptance of president 
bushs initiative 
at the white house bush said i am very pleased with the way 
things are going weve got some good common ground that i 
dont think we had before 
and bushs press secretary marlin fitzwater said the soviet 
response shows that we are on the same wavelength it was a very 
constructive response our ultimate objective is total elimination 
of chemical weapons and it appears that both nations are now ready 
to act 
the soviet position was outlined by foreign minister eduard a 
shevardnadze in a speech to the un general assembly and then by 
karpov at a news conference 
the two sides disagreed on whether the soviet plan went beyond 
bushs initiative but the two approaches clearly differed in two 
significant ways 
bush would have the superpowers retain 2 percent of their 
chemical weapons until all nations capable of building chemical 
weapons sign an international ban 
and as the president explained his proposal monday in a speech 
to the general assembly the united states would keep producing 
new binary weapons while destroying older stocks 
binary weapons are deadly but only when they are mixed 
shevardnadze praised bushs move and said the soviet union 
together with the united states is ready to go further 
he called for a cessation of production at a news conference 
later deputy foreign minister karpov said soviet acceptance was 
conditional on a halt to us production of binary weapons 
it is part of the parcel said karpov the highestranked 
arms control expert in the soviet hierarchy it will not be 
sufficient to get rid of old weapons if the united states is going 
to produce new ones 
a second key difference between the two sides centers on when 
all us and soviet chemical weapons would be destroyed 
bush said the united states was ready to destroy 98 percent of 
its weapons in the first eight years of an agreement with moscow 
the remaining 2 percent would be retained until 40 nations now 
negotiating in geneva agreed on a treaty to ban chemical weapons 
and all nations with the capability to produce them signed the pact 
this would mean an outright ban depended on the approval of such 
nations as iran and iraq and possibly libya which the reagan 
administration says is on the verge of production iraq and iran 
have been accused of using poison gas in their persian gulf war 
that ended last year 
karpov said the soviets were willing to destroy all their 
chemical weapons once the treaty was completed 
we wouldnt bar the treaty entering into force if there is one 
nation capable of producing chemical weapons he said 
karpov said the soviets were not helping any country to 
manufacture chemical weapons he placed the soviet arsenal at 
50000 tons 
bush administration officials have declined to divulge the us 
total the general assumption is that it is about 30000 tons 
shevardnadze also called on the two superpowers to renounce 
the use of chemical weapons under any circumstances 
and the soviet foreign minister said they should employ 
rigorous verification of the cessation of production of chemical 
warfare agents 
shevardnadze and secretary of state james a baker iii agreed 
last week in talks in jackson hole wyo on a twostep plan for 
exchanging information about chemical weapons and for trial 
inspections of stockpiles 
baker had a sevenminute meeting with shevardnadze after the 
foreign minister delivered his speech 
he told reporters he had to study the soviet chemical weapons 
proposal and that it did not appear to go beyond bushs initiative 
but karpov said our proposal is a wider one 
he said moscow was ready to begin negotiations with the united 
states to reduce stockpiles on both sides 
shevardnadze in his speech welcomed bushs initiative and said 
we share the desire to rid mankind of these barbaric weapons 
