two b2 stealth bomber test flights were cut 
short last week once because of a renewed oilpressure problem and 
once because of high winds the pentagon said tuesday 
a planned 5hour flight sept 21 was scrubbed after three hours 
after indications of low oil pressure in the planes no 1 airframe 
accessory drive said pentagon spokesman pete williams 
the batwing bomber is designed to pass through enemy radar 
virtually undetected the accessory drive is the gear box that 
powers the jets generators and controls 
the same problem had forced the crew to scub the second test 
flight of the 530 million plane on aug 16 
as with the second flight the b2 was landed early as a 
precaution williams said the flight crew was in no danger 
four new casings were installed for the stealths fifth test 
flight saturday and no oilpressure problems were encountered 
williams said 
however that flight ended after 77 minutes because of gusty 
winds at the altitude at which the plane was flying william 
said adding that he could not say what the wind strengths were 
it was decided to cut that flight short as a precaution because 
of the stress being placed on the bomber during the particular 
maneuvers being conducted williams said 
that doesnt mean that the plane cant fly at high winds he 
said 
the crew did complete an airrefueling test under which the 
batwing jet purposely stopped just short of its refueling kc10 
aircraft 
williams said the stealth wont be flown again for at least five 
weeks while planned modifications and ground vibration tests 
are done 
the plane has flown a total of 12 hours williams said 
