the white house on tuesday sent congress the 
legislative package containing presidnet bushs campaign spending 
reforms announced earlier this summer 
bush is proposing to abolish nearly all specialinterest 
political action committees which are the source of millions of 
dollars in campaign funds for congressional candidates 
bushs proposal also would bar personal use of leftover campaign 
funds curtail free mailing privileges enjoyed by congress and do 
away with gerrymandering the drawing of crazyquilt congressional 
districts to benefit certain candidates 
the package also would prevent candidates from rolling over 
campaign funds from one election to the next a practice that helps 
many incumbents scare off challengers 
to infuse more money into the system bush would allow the 
national political parties to spend more on their congressional 
candidates than current election law allows 
bush also wants full public disclosure of socalled soft money 
which refers to funds that are prohibited in federal campaigns but 
permitted at the state or local level in many cases critics 
contend that soft money contributions find their way into the 
federal election process anyway 
in a statement to congress accompanying the package he said his 
proposals were designed to reduce substantially the power of 
special economic interests while enhancing the role of individuals 
and political parties 
on political action committees bush would specifically ban 
federal contributions from pacs sponsored by unions corporations 
and trade associations critics contend that campaign donations 
from these pacs give them undue influence over the votes of the 
congress members who receive them 
bush announced the proposals in june and put them into 
legislative form that he sent to congress on tuesday 
he also has announced his support for a pay raise for congress 
members but has sent no specific proposal leaving that effort to 
congress itself 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

