<TEXT>
a new california law sets a limit on 
the amount of fat allowed in school lunches and was the result of a 
lawmakers shock at the quality of food served at a school in her 
district 
the law which goes into effect jan 1 requires the state board 
of education to set fat and cholesterol levels for all school 
lunches and orders the board to force the californias 1000plus 
school districts to follow the standards 
the legislation is aimed at highfat lowfoodvalue lunches 
that often serve as the sole source of a childs daily nourishment 
the bill was signed last week by the governor 
im sad to say that for many children the school lunch they 
eat is the most balanced meal they receive all day said 
assemblywoman jackie speier author of the law this is 
particularly alarming when that lunch consists of a corn dog and 
tater tots 
a group called the public voice for food and health policy 
based in washington dc has issued a report that says the 
federal government supplies about a third of the food used in more 
than 24 million lunches served daily at 91000 schools the foods 
include highfat content items such as ground beef pork luncheon 
meat ham butter cheese and eggs 
health authorities generally agree that the daily fat intake for 
school children should be no more than 30 percent of total calories 
