<TEXT>
marlon brando returns to the screen in a dry white season 
after a lamentable nineyear absence the notsogood news is that 
he appears on the screen less than 10 minutes 
yes he looks bulky resembling raymond burr in his courtroom 
robe yes he affects a british accent how he loves props that 
drew an initial titter from the preview audience but no the 
brando magnetism has not diminished in his long layoff he remains 
a dominating force 
like cry freedom and a world apart a dry white 
season was filmed in zimbabwe and looks at south africas 
apartheid from a white viewpoint the central figure is donald 
sutherland a teacher at an exclusive white boys school he is 
vaguely unsettled by the signs of oppression all around him and by 
the tacit agreement with the governments policy by his family and 
fellow faculty members 
apartheid strikes close to sutherland when his sons playmate 
and the boys father are kidnapped tortured and murdered by the 
special police he enlists the help of the shadowy zakes mokae a 
taxi driver with good connections susan sarandon a liberal 
reporter and a noted defense lawyer played by brando 
sutherlands efforts to seek justice are thwarted and he loses 
his job his wife his standing in the white community and more 
even his own daughter betrays him only one element of hope 
remains he has inculcated his young son with a sense of outrage at 
the vicious repression of the south african regime 
the surehanded direction of euzhan palcy sugar cane alley 
and her talent for drawing the best from actors infuse a dry 
white season with suspense despite the inevitability of the 
outcome she is superb at the handling of action scenes such as the 
massacre of children at soweto focusing on individual human 
tragedy her only annoying technique is the use of extreme 
closeups especially on minor characters 
sutherland is perfect as the rational man whose growing fury at 
the regimes atrocities forces him to take action equally 
effective are janet suzman as his icy unsupportive wife susan 
sarandon as the fearless reporter and jurgen prochnow das 
boot as the embodiment of evil as the special police officer 
the african actors bring substance and authenticity to the film 
especially zakes mokae as sutherlands underground source and 
winston ntshona as the murdered boys father both are south 
african exiles who have brought the antiapartheid message to the 
london and new york theaters 
in brandos two scenes he reemphasizes his position as the 
most exciting film actor of his time lets hope that his recent 
announcement of another retirement was another brando prank 
the mgmua release was produced by paula weinstein and is rated 
r for language and brutal action running time 106 minutes 
