<TEXT>
arthur andersen amp co and price waterhouse 
citing regulatory concerns and other problems announced tuesday 
they had scrapped plans for a merger that would have created the 
worlds biggest accounting firm 
a price waterhouse official who asked not to be identified 
said the key stumbling block to the merger was concern over the 
regulatory environment because the two firms represent so many 
competing companies 
however another source close to the talks who asked not to be 
named confirmed published reports that differences over funding of 
the firms retirement plans the name of the combined firm and 
other issues had hampered the talks 
in a joint statement the chiefs of the two accounting giants 
said the merger discussions were discontinued because differences 
could not be resolved within a realistic time frame 
joseph e connor chairman of price waterhouse and lawrence a 
weinbach andersens chief executive stated both firms have 
emerged from the talks with great respect for one another and 
better insight into the professional service environment in which 
they operate 
the statement said confidentiality agreements had been signed by 
both firms and therefore there will be no public comment by 
either firm on details of the discussions 
the firms originally announced merger talks in july amid a 
backdrop of other mergers among the big eight accounting firms 
aiming to face heightened global competition 
for example analysts say the firms want to be better positioned 
to compete once the 12nation european economic community drops its 
internal trade barriers in 1992 
arthur young amp co and ernst amp whinney combined to form ernst amp 
young now the worlds biggest accounting firm while deloitte 
haskins amp sells joined forces with touche ross amp co forming no 4 
deloitte amp touche 
price waterhouse and andersen announced on sept 5 that they 
would need more time to continue their negotiations 
industry analysts said the justice department had been examining 
the possible ramifications of an andersenprice waterhouse 
combination which would have merged the nations second and 
sixthlargest firms respectively 
one obstacle to the merger was the potential conflict of 
interest in the firms dealings with such major corporate clients 
as international business machines corp and hewlett packard corp 
the price waterhouse official said 
chicagobased andersens consulting division has joint ventures 
with both corporations to develop computer integration products 
while price is the auditor for both companies 
securities and exchange commission rules bar an accounting firm 
from participating in joint ventures with audit clients because of 
possible conflicts of interest 
the official of new yorkbased price waterhouse said the 
nonregulatory issues such as the differences over funding the 
retirement plans were not critical although it is not 
unreasonable to expect each side to have differences over what 
caused the failure to reach agreement 
the official said he wouldnt rule out renewed merger talks 
but not in the near term we might agree to look at it again in 
two or three years from now 
industry observers predict that the value of merging was great 
enough to possibly inspire the firms to deal with and possibly 
overcome the hurdles that scuttled the plan 
i continue to see tremendous benefits to there being a merger 
and tremendous negatives to both firms if there is not a merger 
said james emerson publisher of emersons professional services 
review in bellevue wash 
a merger would have created the worlds largest accounting firm 
reaping 5 billion a year in worldwide revenue and 27 billion in 
us revenue together the firm would have audited 40 percent of 
the fortune 500 companies 
anderson fell to the no 2 spot among us accounting firms 
earlier this year after ernst amp whinney and arthur young merged 
price waterhouse founded 100 years ago in london is the worlds 
oldest accounting firm 
