<TEXT>
opec ministers stepped up bargaining tuesday in a 
lastditch effort to increase the oil cartels production ceiling 
above 195 million barrels a day for the rest of 1989 without 
sending prices into a freefall 
the 13nation organization of petroleum exporting countries 
three times postponed what was expected to be a final round of 
talks to consider a new iranian proposal talks were to resume 
wednesday evening 
it has to cook some iraqi oil minister issam alchalabi 
said of the iranian plan 
but libya immediately threw cold water on the idea we will 
not accept it insisted a senior libyan delegate who demanded 
anonymity 
earlier iranian oil minister gholamreza aqazadeh said his 
country had offered a plan to raise the production ceiling in the 
last quarter of the year iran suggested hiking the cap to between 
205 million barrels a day and 21 million barrels 
the ministers talks have centered on raising the production cap 
from the current 195 million barrel limit to a level between 20 
million barrels a day and 21 million barrels according to 
delegates 
the additional amount under the iranian plan would be divided 
under a formula that would meet the demands of gabon the united 
arab emirates kuwait ecuador and qatar for bigger shares of the 
production pie 
all countries would get larger individual quotas meaning they 
could pump more in the last quarter than now but some would see 
their percentage share of the total output shrink 
it seems there will be a little increase said a senior 
member of one delegation who demanded anonymity but we still 
have different positions its a slow process 
there are some members that are still taking a very hard 
line said another delegate also on condition of anonymity 
the meeting began saturday with the delegates arguing over 
whether the market was strong enough to absorb an increase in 
production without sending prices tumbling 
the cartel has been overproducing pumping more crude than 
allowed under an output agreement signed in june analysts 
estimate opec production at about 22 million barrels daily 
gasoline prices at the pump were likely to remain about the same 
or even fall a few cents in the long term if production were 
increased according to analysts 
the average price of a basket of crudes monitored by opec was 
recently about 1 under the cartels benchmark of 18 a 42gallon 
barrel west texas intermediate the major american grade has been 
trading at about 1950 to 20 a barrel 
the ministers were reported close to an agreement monday but ran 
into trouble getting all countries to sign on to the deal 
kuwait and the united arab emirates have been producing well 
beyond their individual quotas in an effort to press their case for 
higher shares others countries though are unwilling to give in 
to those two nations and want any increase shared proportionately 
analysts say kuwait and the united arab emirates have been 
producing as much as double their quotas of about 1 million barrels 
each 
the ministers could extend the current ceiling until the end of 
the year but analysts say that might leave the impression of 
disarray in the cartels ranks it also could prompt some countries 
to widen their taps to take advantage of the firm market 
opec has predicted that demand in the final quarter will be 22 
million barrels a day 
the ministers are to meet again in late november to hammer out a 
production pact for the first six months of 1990 
this weeks talks were officially held by a monitoring panel 
made up of algeria indonesia iran iraq kuwait nigeria saudi 
arabia and venezuela the other opec members gabon ecuador 
libya qatar and the united arab emirates were invited to attend 
</TEXT>
