<TEXT>
venezuela has dropped its demands for a 50 
percent reduction in its debt to commercial banks and plans to 
offer new proposals in an attempt to revive negotiations with the 
financial institutions according to a published report 
the changes were detailed monday by miguel rodriguez fandeo 
venezuelas minister of planning the new york times reported in 
its tuesday editions 
rodriguez said an agreement was near on a 600 million interim 
loan from the banks the loan would enable the south american 
nation to meet some interest payments missed over the last several 
months in order to create the atmosphere so the negotiating 
process could speed up 
rodriguez interviewed in washington at the annual meetings of 
the world bank and international monetary fund said the changes 
were made to accommodate the realities of the banks he was 
referring to the different legal and accounting rules in differing 
countries 
he added that venezuela had not changed its position in response 
to moves in the last few weeks by three major us banks to 
increase their reserves for bad third world loans the moves by the 
banks were seen as making it more difficult for third world debtors 
to restructure their debts 
instead of its 50 percent reduction in its 21 billion in loans 
from commercial banks a goal the banks rejected venezuela will 
now offer the banks a broad range of options on debt reduction 
rodriguez said 
the options would include reducing the debt by various levels 
starting at 60 percent and going to below the 35 percent level 
negotiated in a debt agreement with mexico banks also would have 
the option of making new loans he said 
offering various debt reduction levels to different banks would 
make it easier to negotiate than trying to reach agreement on one 
number among all banks he said 
